```suggestion
    g.Produces (v ++ p) (w ++ p) :=
  match hvw with | âŸ¨r, hrâŸ© => âŸ¨r, hr.left, hr.right.append_right pâŸ©
```
and similarly throughout
When only one "case", do we put `|` on the same line?
Not usually, but I think it's fine for golfing something trivial, in the same way that we don't usually write `foo; bar`, but sometimes do for trivial proofs.
I think you want to keep both this and the new definition in the docstring

OK, I'll put it back.
And the definitions through which `ContextFreeGrammar.language` is defined shouldn't be here?

I am confused about the philosophy of "Main definitions". When we have a pile of definitions, do we mention only the top one? Because that was almost what was here before. I don't mind including them all tho.

It's supposed to do what it says on the tin. Sometimes you have a lot of `def`s (eg you just defined a new space and are defining a bunch of maps from it) but only a few are important. Those are the ones that should be in the module doc.
So here I should mention `ContextFreeGrammar.Produces`, `ContextFreeGrammar.Derives`, `ContextFreeGrammar.Generates`, `ContextFreeGrammar.language` and `Language.IsContextFree` as well?

I think you should have
```
* `ContextFreeGrammar`: A context-free grammar.
* `ContextFreeGrammar.language g`: The language generated by the given context-free grammar `g`
* `Language.IsContextFree l`: The proposition that the language `l` is generated by some `ContextFreeGrammar`
```
Part of the problem with the current version is that that you are using the description of `language` to describe `IsContextFree`.

All the rest are probably implementation details, but it doesn't make sense to declare `ContextFreeGrammar.language` an implementation detail, since without it, grammars have no API!
Elaborating on what @YaelDillies said, why not `ContextFreeGrammar.Produces` and `ContextFreeGrammar.Derives` and `ContextFreeGrammar.Generates` as main definitions, too?
Possibly I misunderstood "what it says on the tin".
I think of `Produces`/`Derives`/`Generates` all as secondary definitions to `ContextFreeGrammar`.
Isn't `ContextFreeGrammar.language` a secondary definition to `Language.IsContextFree` then?
No, because without that definition you would never have a reason to talk about `ContectFreeGrammar` at all.

I don't understand the philosophy here. In my point of view `Language.IsContextFree` is built on top of `ContextFreeGrammar.language` as well as `ContextFreeGrammar.language` is built on top of `ContextFreeGrammar.Generates` and so on.

It's not about what things are built upon; if I tell you that I have constructed a `ContextFreeGrammar`, what would you guess is the most likely thing I want to do with it? My guess is that the answer is "look at the language it defines".
Yes!
I better do this PR without `Language.IsContextFree` as it should be about prefix and postfix.
